Builds `out/viz-data.json`, the data file the standalone `viz/index.html` viewer reads to let a user drill from category → stroke choices → full outline/rendered text. This is the CLI entry point that wires together the sibling modules (`axis`, `build`, `comments`, `grouping`, `json`, `tree`) in this same `viz_data` binary directory; it does no tree-building logic itself.

Categories come exclusively from explicit `## label` markers in `dict.steno`, scanned via `comments::scan` — ordinary prose comments are never treated as categories. `comments::scan_desc` separately extracts per-entry descriptions used for display. Both scans run against the same raw source string that's also fed to `parse_source`/`expand_dict`, so `dict.steno` is read and parsed independently of the marker scan; if the dict's comment syntax changes, `comments.rs` must be updated in lockstep with the parser's own comment handling.

`root()` locates the workspace root via `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR` joined with `../..` — assumes this binary lives exactly two directories below the workspace root; moving the crate breaks the relative path silently (it would just point at the wrong directory, not error, unless `dict.steno` is missing there).

`run()` is the actual pipeline: load source → scan markers/descriptions → `expand_dict` (with `None` for whatever contextual param that takes) → `build::build(&typed, &markers, &desc_map)` → `json::to_json` → write to `out/viz-data.json`, printing category/node/byte counts to stdout on success. All fallible steps collapse their error type to `String` via `.map_err(|e| e.to_string())`, so callers of `run()` lose the original error type — fine here since `main` only prints and exits, but not reusable if this logic is ever called from another Rust caller expecting structured errors.

`out_line` and `fail` swallow write failures (`let _ =`) intentionally, since there's no fallback channel if stdout/stderr itself is broken.